    <chapter><title>Sets</title>

      <section><title>Definition</title>
        <p>A <term>set</term> is a collection of objects, called <term>members</term> or <term>elements</term>.
        If an element <m>x</m> is a member of a set <m>S</m>we write <m>x \in S</m> 
        and say <m>x</m> is an element of <m>S</m> or <m>x</m> is belongs to <m>S</m> or <m>x</m> is in <m>S</m></p>
      </section>

      <section><title>Axioms</title>
        <p>
          <axiom><title>Extension</title>
            <statement>
              Two groups, <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are equal if and only if
              every member of A is a member of B and every member of <m>B</m> is a member of <m>A</m>
            </statement>
          </axiom>
          <axiom><title>Existence</title></axiom>
          <axiom><title>Foundation</title></axiom>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section><title>Operations</title>
        <introduction>For two sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></introduction>
        <subsection><title>Union</title>
          <p>The set of all elements of A and B</p>
          <p>A set C is the union of sets A and B if it contains all elements of A and all elements of B.</p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection><title>Intersection</title>
        </subsection>
      </section>

